Q/a9c4f65ff37ae49164d90424f108da0681e6e3214cb47d01b64df2a211d43c5e" style=
=3D"text-decoration:underline;color:#d40000;">shared</a> a recent essay fro=
m <em>The New Yorker</em>, =E2=80=9CThe New Literalism Plaguing Today=E2=80=
=99s Biggest Movies.=E2=80=9D The writer, <strong>Namwali Serpell</strong>,=
 argued in the piece that most contemporary cinema=E2=80=94including many o=
f the films that won Academy Awards last week=E2=80=94was =E2=80=9Con the n=
ose or heavy-handed, that it hammers away
at us or beats a dead horse.=E2=80=9D Serpell didn=E2=80=99t <em>quite </em=
>bother to explain how this had happened, but she did observe that the lite=
ralist approach was pervading other parts of our culture. Fashion, she argu=
ed, =E2=80=9Ccapitalizes on a long tail of generic looks=E2=80=9D that are =
decontextualized and endlessly recycled. (=E2=80=9CWe all wear Doc Martens =
but no one is actually goth,=E2=80=9D she wrote.)<br/><br/>Like many essays=
 of this sort, Serpell harps too much on the past and the way things <em>us=
ed to be</em>, and offers
no solution for how to improve things in the future. (Typical academic.) I =
don=E2=80=99t disagree with her thesis, though. In fashion, everything thes=
e days<em> is</em> too on the nose. After all, designers don=E2=80=99t have=
 to be as imaginative as they once did, in part because they don=E2=80=99t =
have to work for their references. They don=E2=80=99t have to go to the lib=
rary to sift through old magazines, or try to remember the shot-by-shot det=
ails of a film they saw a decade ago. Instant access to everything has
changed the design process as much as it has so many other facets of life=
=E2=80=94often rendering it more facile. The debuts of <strong>Haider Acker=
mann</strong> and <strong>Sarah Burton</strong> at Tom Ford and Givenchy, r=
espectively, were so well received this week partly because both designers =
have lived beyond what=E2=80=99s inside their iPhones.</p></div>
